{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01142r8bvc9nHSNvDGW1HSnp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior in the context of the PostToolUse hook issue described. The hook needs to detect when a command creates a PR, even when the command includes newline-separated variable assignments before the `gh` invocation.\n\nLet me think through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: Command segmentation treats newline-separated statements as separate segments, not one monolithic block.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about parsing logic — splitting a string by newlines and treating each as a segment. This is a pure algorithmic/parsing function. No module interaction needed.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed — just string processing.\n\n\n- MOCK-HIDE: No external dependency to mock.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n- INTEGRATION-CHECK: Can be reproduced by calling one function with crafted arguments → Unit.\n- Minimum level: **Unit**\n\n**Behavior 2: A multi-line shell block with variable assignments followed by `gh pr create` is recognized as a PR-create trigger.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the classification logic — given a parsed command/block, does the classifier recognize `gh pr create` as a trigger? This could be a unit test if it's just matching logic, or it could require integration testing depending on whether the classifier needs to understand the full context of the parsed segments.\n\nThe key question is whether segmentation and classification are tightly coupled or separate. If the classifier receives pre-segmented input, I can test it at the unit level. But the bug description suggests the entire block was misclassified, which points to a failure in how segmentation feeds into classification. If these are separate modules that need to interact, this becomes an integration test. The failure mode indicates the segmentation step was skipped before classification